.H 2 "Changing the Network Address of a DCE Machine"
...\" ----------------------------------------------------------------------
...\" 
.P
Occasionally, a machine running DCE will need to change its network address.
DCE stores the network address in several files which need to be updated.
To change a DCE machine's network address, you must perform the
following procedure:
.AL
.LI
Shutdown DCE (by selecting option 4 in the \*Ldce_config\*O Main Menu).
.LI
Change the machine's network address and reboot the operating system,
as needed.
.LI
Remove the machine's CDS cache:
.iS
rm /opt/dcelocal/var/adm/directory/cds/cds_cache*
.iE
.LI
Update the network address in the  \*L/opt/dcelocal/etc/security/pe_site\*O
file.
.LI
Update the network address in the \*L/opt/dcelocal/etc/cds_config\*O
file.
.LI
Restart DCE (by selecting option 3 in the \*Ldce_config\*O Main Menu).
.LI
If necessary, update the following CDS objects:
.iS
    \*L/.:/hosts/\*Vhostname\*L/self\*O
    \*L/.:/hosts/\*Vhostname\*L/dts-entity\*O
.iE
.P
These CDS objects contain bindings that are exported when the cell is
configured by the \*Ldce_config\*O script, but are not checked when daemons
are restarted.
.P
In order to ensure that the \*Lself\*O and \*Ldts_entity\*O objects have
the proper updated address, run the \*Ldcecp\*O \*Lobject show\*O
command for each object:
.iS
\*Cdcecp>\*O  \*Lobject show /.:/hosts/\*Vhostname\*L/\*Vobject\*O
.iE
If the network address listed in the \*LTower\*O attribute is incorrect,
change it to an appropriate one.
.P
.zA "def,13556,R1.2.2,correct continuation character spacing"
To update the network address of the \*Lself\*O object, use the
\*Ldcecp\*O 
\*Lrpcentry unexport\*O command to unexport the object's binding:
.iS
\*Cdcecp>\*O \*Lrpcentry unexport  /.:/hosts/\*Vhostname\*L/\*Vobject \*L-interface \*Vinterface_id\*O \\
\*C> \*L-object \*Vif_uuid\*O
.iE
.P
The UUID value \*Vif_uuid\*O for the object can be obtained by running
the following command:
.iS
\*Cdcecp>\*O \*Lrpcentry show /.:/hosts/\*Vhostname\*L/\*Vobject \*L-interface \*Vinterface_id\*O \\
\*C> \*L-object \*Vif_uuid\*O
.iE
.P
Now update the object with the correct (new) network address.  The command
to use is:
.iS
\*Cdcecp>\*O \*Lrpcentry export /.:/hosts/\*Vhostname\*L/\*Vobject \*L-interface \*Vinterface_id\*O \\
\*C> \*L-binding \*Vprotocol_sequence\*L  -object \*Vif_uuid\*O
.iE
.zZ "def,13556,R1.2.2,correct continuation character spacing"
.P
The procedure for updating the \*Ldts-entity\*O object's network address
differs from that for other CDS objects.  First, stop the
\*Ldtsd\*O process on the target host.  Then, delete the
\*L/.:/hosts/\*Vhostname\*L/dts-entity\*O object (by using the
\*Ldcecp\*O \*Lobject delete\*O command).  Finally, you must
restart the \*Ldtsd\*O process (using \*Ldce_config\*O).
.LI
If DFS is used in a DCE cell, you must also issue the following command
for every DFS server  (\*Lflserver\*O) that has undergone a network address
change:
.iS
\*C> \*Lfts edserver -server \*Vold.ip.addr\*L -changeaddr \*Vnew.ip.addr\*O
.iE
.P
You can then restart all of the DFS servers in the cell
so that they recognize the new address.  You may also have to stop and
restart DCE (using \*Ldce_config\*O), as well, and remove the CDS cache
before restarting the servers.  For instructions on how to remove the
CDS cache, see the \*(Ac.
.LE
.H 2 "CDS Maintenance Tasks"
.iX "CDS" "maintenance tasks"
.iX "maintenance tasks" "CDS"
.iX "tasks" "maintenance" "CDS"
CDS components, including clerks, servers, and clearinghouses, are
largely self-regulating.
Except for routine monitoring, CDS
requires little intervention for system administration.
.iX "clearinghouse"
.iX "CDS" "control program"
When intervention is required, CDS provides system administration tools
to help you monitor and manage the CDS namespace and CDS servers.
.P
You can use the DCE control program (\*Ldcecp\*O) commands
described in Chapter 15 of
...\" Module 3, "Using the CDS Control Program,"
the \*(Ac
to create and manage the components of a CDS
namespace.
.P
You can also manage CDS by using the CDS Browser utility (\*Lcdsbrowser\*O)
to view the namespace.  The \*Lcdsbrowser\*O utility enables you to monitor
growth in the size and number of CDS directories in your namespace. 
You can use the \*Lcdsbrowser\*O utility to display an
overall directory structure, as well as the contents of directories.
Chapter 19
...\" Module 3, "Viewing the Structure and Contents of a Namespace,"
of the \*(Ac discusses the \*Lcdsbrowser\*O utility.
.iX "Browser"
.iX "administration tools" "Browser"
.iX "CDS" "Browser"
.iX "cell namespace" "viewing contents"
.P
If you have a large organization, you can improve efficiency by
having one system administrator responsible for CDS servers
and another system administrator responsible for the namespace.
You can delegate responsibility for a subtree of the namespace to another
administrator by granting access control rights to that person.
.P
For more detailed information on CDS maintenance tasks, see
the \*(Ac.
.H 3 "Monitoring CDS"
.iX "CDS" "monitoring"
.P
CDS monitoring tasks fall into the following two categories:
.ML
.LI
Monitoring the namespace
.iX "cell namespace" "monitoring"
.ML
.LI
Monitor the size and usage of clearinghouses and determine the need for new
CDS servers and clearinghouses.  Plan and oversee the configuration of these
new servers and clearinghouses.
.LI
Maintain and monitor a map of the namespace.
.LE
.LE
.ML
.LI
Monitoring CDS servers
.ML
.LI
Enable event logging, monitor CDS events, and solve system-specific problems
if they arise.  If necessary, notify the namespace administrator of problems
that can affect other CDS servers or clerks.
.LI
Monitor the success of skulks that originate at the server.
.iX "skulks"
A \*Eskulk\*O is a method of updating all replicas through repeated operations.
.LI
Monitor the size and usage of the server's clearinghouse and, if necessary,
discuss with the namespace administrator the need to relocate some replicas
or create a new clearinghouse.
.LI
Monitor and tune system parameters that affect or are affected by CDS
server operation.
.LE
.LE
.nS note
When monitoring memory usage for CDS servers, it is important to
understand that memory remains allocated under certain conditions. Memory
associated with objects remains allocated until a skulk is
successfully completed. Memory associated with directories remains
allocated until the server is disabled and restarted.
.nE
For detailed discussions of these tasks, see 
Chapter 17 of
...\" "Managing Clerks, Servers, and Clearinghouses" in \*VModule 3\*O.
the \*(Ac.
.H 3 "Managing CDS"
.P
CDS management tasks fall into the following two categories:
.ML
.LI
Managing the namespace
.ML
.LI
Oversee the creation of new directories and assign names according to a
standard, or enforce established guidelines in the assigning of names.
(Beyond a certain level in the directory hierarchy, you
can delegate the responsibility of creating and maintaining directories.
You need to keep track of the new directories being
created to make sure they are appropriately replicated.)
.LI
Determine the default access control policy.
.LI
Administer and enforce the established access control policy for directories
and entries.
.LI
Determine where and when new replicas of a directory are necessary.
.LI
Create soft links for objects that change locations or for objects that need
to be renamed. An \*Eobject\*O is a resource, such as a disk, an application,
or a node, that is given a CDS name.  A name plus its attributes make up an \*Eobject entry\*O.  A \*Esoft link\*O is a pointer that
provides an alternate name for an object entry.
.P
Publicize and encourage the use of the new names so that
eventually the soft links can be deleted.
.LI
Solve or direct the resolution of problems involving multiple CDS servers.
.LE
.LI
Managing CDS servers
.ML
.LI
Manage access control on directories and objects, and monitor the size and
usage of directories in the server's clearinghouse.  Create new directories,
possibly with the namespace administrator, when necessary.
.LI
Create new objects in directories or oversee their creation. (Beyond a certain
level in the directory hierarchy, you also can delegate
the responsibility of maintaining directories and the objects in them.)
.LI
Add new administrators to the \*Lcds-admin\*O security group.
.LE
.LE
.P
Chapters 16, 17, 18, and 20
...\" \*VModule 3\*O
...\" "Controlling Access to CDS Names"
...\" "Managing Clerks, Servers, and Clearinghouses"
...\" "Managing CDS Directories"
...\" "Restructuring a Namespace"
of the \*(Ac
provide detailed information about how to perform these tasks.
.H 3 "CDS Security and Access Control"
.P
The DCE control program (\*Ldcecp\*O) and CDS ACL Manager work together
to manage authorization in CDS.  To modify, add, delete, or view ACL entries
in the CDS namespace, use \*Ldcecp\*O \*Lacl\*O commands.  When
\*Ldcecp\*O issues a request to perform an operation on a CDS
object, the CDS ACL Manager checks permissions, based on ACL entries,
and grants or denies the request.  The CDS ACL Manager is an integral part
of the \*Lcdsd\*O and \*Lcdsadv\*O processes.  
.P
Chapter 16
...\" "Controlling Access to CDS Names" in \*VModule 3\*O
of the \*(Ac
provides detailed information about handling CDS security and access control,
including guidelines for setting up access control in a new namespace.
.iX "cell namespace" "security"
.iX "access control" "in the namespace"
.H 2 "GDS Maintenance Tasks"
.iX "GDS" "maintenance tasks"
.iX "maintenance tasks" "GDS"
.iX "tasks" "maintenance" "GDS"
GDS provides a menu-driven interface for performing the maintenance tasks
described in the following subsections.
For more detailed information on the GDS maintenance tasks, see
the \*(Ax.
.H 3 "Monitoring GDS"
.P
You can monitor GDS by displaying directory system status information with
the GDS interface or by using the trace system to log directory processes.
.P
The GDS interface allows you to do the following:
.ML
.LI
Display directory system status information, which
shows if a directory is active or inactive, what processes are available,
how many
processes are available, and if the trace system is active or inactive.
.LI
Activate the trace system, which
starts the trace system for logging directory processes.
.LI
Deactivate (or stop) the trace system.
.LE
.P
For more information on these functions, see 
...\" Chapter 28.
...\" \*VModule 3\*O, the chapter entitled "Administration of GDS."
the \*(Ax.
.P
GDS maintains log files for each of the
following processes:
.ML
.LI
The DUA process
.LI
The Cache process
.LI
The Client-stub process
.LI
The Server-stub processes
.LI
The DSA processes
.LI
The GDS system administration process
.LI
The Monitoring process
.LE
For more information on the location, contents, and creation of log files, see 
...\" Chapter 27.
...\" "Starting, Monitoring and Stopping the System" in \*VModule 3\*O.
the \*(Ax.
.H 3 "Managing GDS"
.P
GDS provides the following functions for management tasks:
.ML
.LI
Administrative Functions
.P
This directory management function, which is available
after logging into a DSA,
supports administration of the contents
of the GDS database, both local and remote.  You can choose from the 
four types of administration functions in the following
list. These administration functions allow you to administer objects,
shadows, trees, and schema for your
directory service system.  A GDS \*Eschema\*O is a set of rules and constraints
for tree structure, object class definitions, attribute types, and
syntaxes that characterize the Directory Information Tree (DIT).
.ML
.LI
Object Administration
.P
This function controls objects and changes their attributes.
.LI
Schema Administration
.P
This function modifies the Object Class Table, Structure Rule Table, and
Attribute Table to store a new schema in the Directory
System Agent.
.LI
Shadow Administration
.P
This function executes, schedules, or modifies shadow jobs for updating.
.LI
Tree Administration
.P
This function adds, deletes, or modifies subtrees.
.LE
.LI
Administrative Functions Under the DUA Cache
.P
This directory management function supports the administration of the contents
of the local DUA cache database.
You can choose from the two types of administration functions in
the following list.  These administration functions allow you to administer the
objects stored in the local DUA cache database and the cache update job.
.ML
.LI
Object Administration
.P
This function controls objects stored in the local DUA cache database and
changes their attributes.
.LI
Cache Update
.P
This function displays, activates, or deactivates the Cache Update job, or
changes its update frequency.
.LE
.LI
Activation of a directory system installation
.P
This directory management function
activates the directory installation by starting the background
processes of GDS.
.LI
Deactivation of a directory system installation
.P
This directory management function
ends the background processes of GDS. All
running directory processes are ended, but running operations are not
interrupted, and the data consistency of the managed data is retained.
.P
.LE
.P
For more information on these directory management functions, see
...\" Chapter 28.
...\" "Administration of the Global Directory Service" in \*VModule 3\*O.
the \*(Ax.
.H 3 "Backing Up GDS Data Files"
You can back up directory system data files in GDS by selecting the entry
that saves the local data files to diskette or tape from the function
entries in the menu mask.
The save process backs up all the local data files (local DSA data, DUA cache
data) that belong to your directory system.
.P
GDS has a password feature that protects the directory system
data files on the data medium. The use of this password is
optional when saving data, but you must use
the password when loading files that are saved with a password.
.P
For more information on saving directory system data files, see 
...\" Chapter 28.
...\" \*VModule 3\*O entitled "Administration of the Global Directory Service."
the \*(Ax.
.H 3 "Changing Global Directory Configurations"
The GDS interface has a function,
\*CConfiguration of a directory system\*O, that enables you to
enter, delete, display, or change configuration data, such as the number of
clients or servers to be activated.
For more information on this function, see 
...\" Chapter 28.
...\" \*VModule 3\*O, "Administration of the Global Directory Service."
the \*(Ax.
...\" \*EOSF DCE Administration Guide\(emExtended Services\*O.
.H 2 "DTS Maintenance Tasks"
.iX  "DTS" "maintenance tasks"
.iX  "maintenance tasks" "DTS"
.iX  "tasks" "maintenance" "DTS"
.iX  "dtscp"
Like CDS, DTS is largely self-regulating once configuration of the service
is complete.  However, there are times when you need to intervene.
Use \*Ldcecp\*O to perform the following DTS configuration and
management tasks:
.ML
.LI
Identify system clock problems.
.LI
Adjust the system clocks.
.LI
Change DTS attributes for varying WAN conditions.
.LI
Modify the system configuration when the network environment changes.
.LE
.P
For more detailed information on DTS maintenance tasks, see
the \*(Ac.
.H 3 "Managing the Distributed Time Service"
.P
You can use \*Ldcecp\*O to create and
enable DTS. Once this is done, you can perform routine
management tasks, such as enhancing performance,
reconfiguring the network, and changing local time.
.P
Several commands and characteristics
modify and improve the performance of your network.
The \*Ldts modify\*O command changes the values of many
of these characteristics. The \*Ldts show\*O command displays the values
of characteristics at any time. The following are some of the
tasks you can accomplish using the DTS commands and the
characteristics of DTS that can be set:
.ML
.LI
Display or change the number of servers
that must supply time values to the system
before DTS can synchronize
the system clock.
.LI
Display or change the inaccuracy limit that forces the system to
synchronize in order to bring the inaccuracy back to an acceptable level.
.LI
Display or change the interval at which you want clock synchronization to
occur.
.LI
Display or change the reaction to a faulty system clock.
.LI
Display or change the settings that indicate how often to query servers.
.LE
.P
...\" For more information about these commands and characteristics, see 
...\" Chapter 36.
...\" \*VModule 4\*O, "Managing the Distributed Time Service."
...\" the \*(Ac.
Refer to the \*(Ac
for more information on these and the following tasks:
.ML
.LI
Creating and enabling DTS.
.LI
Assigning the courier role to servers to facilitate communications to
other parts of your network.
.LI
Matching the epoch number
